OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F318A1778746039
OL,3,CWhat is behind the 'eerie' spring
OL,4,Cphenomenon covering Britain's
OL,5,Chedgerows?
OL,7,FBut the truth is stranger - and far
OL,8,Folder.
OL,10,FIt is the work of ermine moth
OL,11,Fcaterpillars. The tiny insects are
OL,12,Fcapable of transforming ordinary
OL,13,Fhedges into creepy silk cocoons.
OL,15,FAcross southern and eastern England in
OL,16,Fparticular, sightings have surged
OL,17,Ffollowing a warm start to the season
OL,18,Fand ideal breeding conditions.
OL,20,FWhat are Ermine moth caterpillars?
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G2/10
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BNat News CNat TV FClean Feed
FL,319,300,200,140,000,100
PN,31803
SC,0003
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F318A1778746039
OL,3,CWhat is behind the 'eerie' spring
OL,4,Cphenomenon covering Britain's
OL,5,Chedgerows?
OL,7,FErmine moth caterpillars are small and
OL,8,Fsmooth-bodied, with a row of black
OL,9,Fdots on their back.
OL,11,FThey belong to the Yponomeuta family.
OL,12,FThe caterpillars hatch in spring into
OL,13,FErmine moths - so named because they
OL,14,Fresemble Ermine fur.
OL,16,FHundreds or even thousands of them
OL,17,Fcluster together and feed communally,
OL,18,Fspinning huge sheets of protective
OL,19,Fsilk around trees and hedgerows as
OL,20,Fthey eat.
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G3/10
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
