PN,31807
SC,0007
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F318A1778746039
OL,3,CWhat is behind the 'eerie' spring
OL,4,Cphenomenon covering Britain's
OL,5,Chedgerows?
OL,7,FThe silk protects them while they feed
OL,8,Faggressively for several weeks before
OL,9,Fpupating into moths in early summer.
OL,11,FThen, by July, most affected hedges
OL,12,Fbegin producing fresh leaves again.
OL,14,FUltimately, no matter how dead the
OL,15,Fhedges look, there's no lasting damage.
OL,17,FIn fact, ecologists say the insects
OL,18,Fare also an important food source for
OL,19,Fbirds and part of Britain's wider
OL,20,Fecosystem.
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G7/10
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
